, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England"},"en":{"1510–1555":"1510–1555","1520–1609":"1520–1609","1530–1616":"1530–1616","1487–1524":"1487–1524","1500–1543":"1500–1543","1524":"1524","1555":"1555","1500":"1500","1510":"1510","1543":"1543","Abt 1530":"about 1530","1487":"1487","1520":"1520","1530":"1530","1609":"1609","1616":"1616","1549":"1549","Handsworth, Staffordshire, England":"Handsworth, Staffordshire, England","Amersham, Buckinghamshire, England":"Amersham, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Hampshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Saunders","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Surrey and Kent): variant of   Sander  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Sander","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt, Erna, Erwin, Fritz, Manfred, Bernhard, Dieter, Franz, Gerda, Klaus, Wolfgang.","English (Cumberland), Dutch, German, and Swedish: from the personal name <i>Sander</i>, a shortened form of   Alexander  . Compare   Saunders  .","German: topographic name for someone who lived on sandy soil, from   Sand   1 + <i>-er</i>, suffix denoting an inhabitant."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":39,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholas Thomas Saunders was born in 1510, in Staffordshire, England, his father, Sir Richard Saunders, was 23 and his mother, Alice Wilford, was 10. He had at least 1 daughter with Alice Walsingham. He died in 1555, in Handsworth, Staffordshire, England, at the age of 45."},"et":{